    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f914cd02166793195d9d950503f8f739?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1352170,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1291492,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1291492/controlaltdel",
                "reputation": 35259,
                "display_name": "ControlAltDel",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 7,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1459868441,
            "creation_date": 1459868441,
            "body": "<p>The semicolon means that the statement below won't be executed until the loop has exited. Your case, the loop is taking p to the end of the list (the last element) and then the next statement is assigning its next value to the new element<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 36430056,
            "question_id": 36430012
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/FQ3JN.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 1334069,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1277259,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1277259/kevino",
                "reputation": 4423,
                "display_name": "KevinO",
                "accept_rate": 75
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1459869564,
            "creation_date": 1459868465,
            "body": "<p>Well, the way it is constructed right now as <code>for(p=head; (q=p.getNext())!=null; p=q);<\/code>, the for loop has an empty body. The variables <code>p<\/code> and <code>q<\/code> through the <code>p.getNext()<\/code> and <code>p=q<\/code> assignments are updating. Then it is executing the <code>p.setNext(node);<\/code> a single time.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>EDIT<\/strong>: As to why the code is working <em>with<\/em> the semi-colon, it is because you are advancing the variables p and q over the list. While the <code>for<\/code> loop with the empty body is fine, I think traditionally one sees a <code>while<\/code> loop.<\/p>\n\n<p>The indentation of the <code>p.setNode(node);<\/code> makes it appear as if the statement were related to the <code>for<\/code> loop, but it really isn't, as the goal is to find the end of the linked list by iterating over it.<\/p>\n\n<p>(note: others made similar points while I was typing this answer)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 36430066,
            "question_id": 36430012,
            "last_edit_date": 1459869564
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/85c7eed792f97e43110fa04f6143c349?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 2591971,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2246488,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2246488/james-wierzba",
                "reputation": 17798,
                "display_name": "James Wierzba",
                "accept_rate": 47
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1459868446,
            "creation_date": 1459868446,
            "body": "<p>it needs to be removed, it is causing it to do nothing in the loop. <\/p>\n\n<p>The loop will execute the next single block of code after the loop. Either one statement, or one { }  code block. <\/p>\n\n<p>In this case, you have one statement <code>;<\/code>, so it \"executes\" and does nothing, and then will call your <code>p.setNext(node);<\/code> after the loop ends.<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public void insertAtEnd() throws IOException {\n        LinkedList node=new LinkedList();\n        System.out.println(\"Enter an element\");\n        int value=Integer.parseInt(br.readLine());\n        node.setData(value);\n        LinkedList p,q;\n        for(p=head; (q=p.getNext())!=null; p=q)\n            p.setNext(node);\n    }\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 36430058,
            "question_id": 36430012
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/xF37X.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 5051719,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 4056099,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/4056099/noseknowsall",
                "reputation": 4634,
                "display_name": "NoseKnowsAll",
                "accept_rate": 89
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1459869653,
            "creation_date": 1459869252,
            "body": "<p>The semicolon is essentially transforming what you appear to want to do because of your indentation:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>for(p=head; (q=p.getNext())!=null; p=q)\n{\n    p.setNext(node);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>into the following:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>for(p=head; (q=p.getNext())!=null; p=q)\n{\n}\np.setNext(node);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>So with the semicolon your loop is executing nothing at every iteration. Then, after it has finished executing, you're running <code>p.setNext(node);<\/code> exactly once.<\/p>\n\n<p>Usually you can avoid this problem in the future by explicitly writing your curly braces as I have done in these two code segments. It is unclear exactly which code segment you are trying to accomplish right now.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 36430355,
            "question_id": 36430012,
            "last_edit_date": 1459869653
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/9B4kt.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 3380175,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2837359,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2837359/manikant-gautam",
                "reputation": 3591,
                "display_name": "Manikant Gautam",
                "accept_rate": 67
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1459869767,
            "creation_date": 1459869319,
            "body": "<p>The for statement provides a compact way to iterate over a range of values. Programmers often refer to it as the \"for loop\" because of the way in which it repeatedly loops until a particular condition is satisfied. The general form of the for statement can be expressed as follows:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>for (initialization; termination; increment) {\n    //statement(s)\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>When using this version of the for statement, keep in mind that:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>The initialization expression initializes the loop; it's executed once, \nas the loop begin<\/li>\n<li>When the termination expression evaluates to false, the loop terminates.<\/li>\n<li>The increment expression is invoked after each iteration through the loop; it is perfectly acceptable for this expression to increment or decrement a value.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>In your case, the loop is taking p to the end of the list (the last element) and then the next statement is assigning its next value to the new element<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 36430385,
            "question_id": 36430012,
            "last_edit_date": 1459869767
        }
    ],
